<bdy>

<b>Query by humming</b> (<b>QbH</b>) is a music retrieval system that branches off the original classification systems of title, artist, composer, and genre. It normally applies to songs or other music with a distinct single theme or melody. The system involves taking a user-hummed <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../735/37735.xml">
melody</link> (input <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../390/679390.xml">
query</link>) and comparing it to an existing <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../377/8377.xml">
database</link>.  The system then returns a ranked list of music closest to the input query. <p>

One example of this would be a system involving a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../437/1560437.xml">
portable media player</link> with a built-in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../886/65886.xml">
microphone</link> that allows for faster <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../149/19386149.xml">
searching</link> through <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../723/53723.xml">
media</link> files.</p>
<p>

The <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../224/185224.xml">
MPEG-7</link> standard includes provisions for QbH music searches.</p>

